Several experimental studies have shown that the relaxed charge transfer (CT) state at the D/A interface is the main precursor for the charge separation process7–9. The overall energy loss during the charge generation can, therefore, be separated into two components: the exothermic transition from the S1 to CT states and the subsequent endothermic transition from the CT to CS states, written as1Egopt-ECS=Egopt-ECT-ECS-ECT,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_{\mathrm{g}}^{{\mathrm{opt}}} - E_{{\mathrm{CS}}} = \left( {E_{\mathrm{g}}^{{\mathrm{opt}}} - E_{{\mathrm{CT}}}} \right) - \left( {E_{{\mathrm{CS}}} - E_{{\mathrm{CT}}}} \right),$$\end{document}where ECT is the lowest energy of the CT state. Egopt − ECT represents the energetic loss to form the CT state and ECS − ECT corresponds to the binding energy of the charge pairs in the CT state.

